<p class="next"><a href="../index.htm">Media</a> > <a href="index.htm">Change</a> > Silent to sound</p>

<h7>Hollywood goes for sound</h7>

<p>When sound arrived, it happened quickly. In 1928 the seven Hollywood majors
released 220 <img border="0" src="silent.gif" width="12" height="12">
silent&nbsp;films and 74 sound films, of which 41 had only <img border="0" src="sound1.gif" width="12" height="12">
synchronised music and sound effects, 23 were <img border="0" src="Sound_2.gif" width="12" height="12">
part talkie and only 10, all from Warner Bros, were <img border="0" src="Sound_3.gif" width="12" height="12">
all talkie. Universal and Paramount in particular were still heavily committed
to silent productions.<br>
 </p>

<p class="boldlaw">Majors' film releases in 1928<br>
<img border="0" src="Sound_shift_1.GIF" width="510" height="307"></p>

<p>In 1929 the balance had shifted radically. By now there were 166 <img border="0"
src="Sound_3.gif" width="12" height="12"> all talkie releases, 50 <img border="0"
src="Sound_2.gif" width="12" height="12"> part talkie and 36 with only <img border="0"
src="sound1.gif" width="12" height="12"> music and effects. <img border="0"
src="silent.gif" width="12" height="12"> Silent releases had dwindled to only 38
out of a total of 290.<br>
</p>

<p class="boldlaw">Majors' film releases in 1929<br>
<img border="0" src="Sound_shift_2.GIF" width="510" height="312"></p>

<p class="date">Source of data: Joel W Finler: The Hollywood Story, 1988</p>
